<TITLE> India 384-7 at tea </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Chittagong, Jan 20 (bdnews24.com)  Despite losing the wicket Sachin Tendulkar in the post lunch session, India had built a strong lead on the fourth day of the first Test against Bangladesh at the Zohur Ahmed Chowdhury Stadium in Chittagong on Wednesday. By tea, India were 384-7, which gave them a lead of 385. VVS Laxman was batting on 51 and Zaheer Khan 17 off 11 balls. Rubel Hossain grabbed the prized wicket of Tendulkar when he had the first-innings centurion trapped leg-before-wicket for 16 with the score on 272. And then Yuvraj Singh was dismissed having added 41 runs for the sixth wicket. The last wicket to fall was Dinesh Karthik (27) was superbly caught by a diving Rubel after going for quick runs. India, who began the fourth day on 122-1, lost three wickets before going to lunch on 259-4. Nightwatchman Amit Mishra fell having completed a maiden Test half-century after 66 runs were added in the first hour of play that began 45 minutes early. They then lost Gautam Gambhir after the opener made 116, it was his ninth Test century and second against the Tigers in Chittagong. He added 45 quick runs for the third wicket with Rahul Dravid before becoming Shafiul Islam's first Test wicket. Gambhir's century was his consecutive fifth and meant he joined an exclusive club of four batsmen led by late Sir Donald Bradman with six. Dravid was run out for 24 before the b
